1. FEATURES
-----------

- Directory tree rendering (ASCII art)
- File content capture with configurable size limit
- SHA256 hashing for every file
- Dual output: JSON (structured) or Markdown (human-readable)
- Respects .gitignore, .snapcatignore, and custom ignore files
- Configurable via CLI flags, .snapcatconfig file, or SNAPCAT_* env vars
- Parallel file reading using Rayon
- Rich error diagnostics with miette
- Usable as both a CLI tool and a Rust library


2. INSTALLATION
---------------

2.1 Pre-built binaries
    Download the appropriate archive from the GitHub Releases page.
    Example for Linux x86_64:
      curl -LO https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat/releases/download/cli-v0.1.0/snapcat-x86_64-linux.tar.gz
      tar -xzf snapcat-x86_64-linux.tar.gz
      sudo install -m 755 snapcat /usr/local/bin/
      snapcat --help

    macOS (Intel/Apple Silicon) and Windows packages are also provided.

2.2 Build from source
    Requirements: Rust (edition 2024+), Git.
      git clone https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat.git
      cd snapcat
      cargo build --release
      ./target/release/snapcat --help

2.3 Install via cargo
      cargo install --git https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat.git


3. QUICK START
--------------

    snapcat
      Runs with defaults, prints JSON to stdout.

    snapcat -o snapshot.json
      Saves JSON output to a file.

    snapcat -f markdown -o report.md
      Generates a Markdown report.


4. COMMAND-LINE USAGE
---------------------

    snapcat [OPTIONS] [PATH]

    PATH
        Target directory. Defaults to current directory (".").

    Options:
        -f, --format <FORMAT>
            Output format: json or markdown. Default: json.

        -o, --output <FILE>
            Write output to FILE instead of stdout.

        -v, --verbose
            Enable verbose (trace) logging.

        --max-depth <N>
            Maximum directory depth to traverse. (None = unlimited)

        --include-hidden
            Include hidden files and directories.

        --follow-symlinks
            Follow symbolic links (caution: may cause loops).

        -j, --jobs <N>
            Number of parallel threads for file reading.
            Default: number of logical CPUs.

        --max-file-size <N>
            Maximum file size in bytes to read. Files exceeding
            this are skipped. Default: 10,000,000 (10 MB).

    Examples:
        snapcat -f markdown -o full.md
        snapcat --max-depth 3 --include-hidden
        snapcat -j 4 --max-file-size 5242880   # 5 MB


5. CONFIGURATION
----------------

Snapcat can be configured through three layers, applied in the following
order (latter overrides former):
    1. .snapcatconfig file
    2. Environment variables (prefix SNAPCAT__)
    3. CLI flags

5.1 Configuration file (.snapcatconfig)
    Place a file named .snapcatconfig in the working directory (or any
    location supported by the `config` crate, such as XDG config dirs).
    The file can contain any of these keys:

        format           : "json" | "markdown"
        output           : "/path/to/output"
        max_depth        : 5
        include_hidden   : true | false
        follow_symlinks  : true | false
        ignore_files     : [".snapcatignore", ".myignore"]
        max_file_size    : 10000000
        verbose          : true | false
        jobs             : 4

    If absent, sensible defaults are used.

5.2 Environment variables
    Prefix SNAPCAT__ and use double underscores as separators:
        SNAPCAT__FORMAT=markdown
        SNAPCAT__OUTPUT=/tmp/snap.md
        SNAPCAT__MAX_DEPTH=3
        SNAPCAT__INCLUDE_HIDDEN=true

    Booleans accept "true" or "false" (case-insensitive).

5.3 Precedence
    CLI flags have highest priority, followed by environment variables,
    then the config file. Defaults are used when nothing is set.


6. OUTPUT FORMATS
-----------------

6.1 JSON
    A pretty-printed JSON object with two top-level keys:
        "tree"  : string containing the rendered directory tree.
        "files" : array of objects, each representing a successfully
                  read file.

    Example structure:
        {
          "tree": "project/\n├── src\n│   ├── main.rs\n│   └── lib.rs\n...",
          "files": [
            {
              "path": "src/main.rs",
              "content": "fn main() { ... }",
              "sha256": "e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb924..."
            }
          ]
        }

6.2 Markdown
    A human-readable document:
        # Snapcat Output

        ```
        project/
        ├── src
        │   ├── main.rs
        │   └── lib.rs
        ```

        ## Files

        ### src/main.rs
        ```
        fn main() { ... }
        ```
        SHA256: `e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb924...`

    Each file gets its own section with a code block and hash.


7. LIBRARY USAGE (Rust API)
----------------------------

Add Snapcat to your Cargo.toml:
    [dependencies]
    snapcat = { git = "https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat.git" }

7.1 Modules overview
    The library exposes these public modules:
        - snapcat::core        (cat, tree)
        - snapcat::handler     (config, error)
        - snapcat::utils       (fmt, ignore)
        - snapcat::types       (SnapOutput, FileEntry, TreeNode, NodeKind)

    Re‑exported items:
        - snapcat::snap        (function)
        - snapcat::output      (function)
        - snapcat::handler::config::{SnapConfig, OutputFormat}
        - snapcat::handler::error::SnapError

7.2 Key types

    7.2.1 SnapConfig
        Configuration struct holding all runtime settings.
        Fields:
            format          : OutputFormat
            output          : Option<std::path::PathBuf>
            max_depth       : Option<usize>
            follow_symlinks : bool
            include_hidden  : bool
            ignore_files    : Vec<String>
            max_file_size   : Option<u64>
            verbose         : bool
            jobs            : Option<usize>

        Methods:
            - SnapConfig::default() -> Self
                Creates a configuration with sensible defaults.
            - SnapConfig::load( ... ) -> Result<Self, SnapError>
                Merges CLI parameters, environment variables, and
                the config file.

    7.2.2 OutputFormat
        Enum:
            Json
            Markdown

    7.2.3 SnapOutput
        The final result of a snapshot operation.
        Fields:
            tree  : String    (textual directory tree)
            files : Vec<FileEntry>

    7.2.4 FileEntry
        A single file record.
        Fields:
            path    : String
            content : String
            sha256  : String

    7.2.5 SnapError
        Enum covering all possible errors. Variants include:
            IgnoreFileRead       (path, source)
            FileReadError        (path, source)
            FileTooLarge         (path, size, max)
            DirNotFound          (path)
            NotADirectory        (path)
            OutputCreateError    (path, source)
            UnsupportedFormat    (String)
            ConfigLoadError      (source)
            InvalidConfig        (msg)
            FormatError          (msg)
            InternalError        (String)

        Implements std::error::Error, miette::Diagnostic,
        and From<config::ConfigError>.

7.3 Public functions

    7.3.1 snap(root: &std::path::Path, config: &SnapConfig) -> Result<SnapOutput, SnapError>
        Walks the directory tree, reads file contents, and builds
        a complete snapshot. Uses parallel processing for file I/O.

    7.3.2 output(result: SnapOutput, config: &SnapConfig) -> Result<(), SnapError>
        Formats the snapshot according to config.format and either
        writes it to config.output or prints to stdout.

7.4 Integration example
    use snapcat::handler::config::{SnapConfig, OutputFormat};
    use snapcat::{snap, output};

    fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
        let config = SnapConfig {
            format: OutputFormat::Markdown,
            output: Some("snapshot.md".into()),
            ..Default::default()
        };

        let result = snap(std::path::Path::new("."), &config)?;
        output(result, &config)?;
        Ok(())
    }


8. ERROR HANDLING
-----------------

All errors are structured, carry diagnostic codes, and often include
helpful suggestions. For example:

    Error: Directory 'no/such/path' not found
      Diagnostic code: snapcat::tree::not_found

    Error: File too large 'big.log': 20000000 bytes (max: 10000000)
      Diagnostic code: snapcat::io::file_too_large

When using the library, handle SnapError explicitly to react to
specific failures (e.g., skip oversized files gracefully).


9. EXAMPLES
-----------

- JSON snapshot of the whole project (defaults):
      snapcat -o full.json

- Markdown document, suitable for feeding an LLM (max 1 MB per file):
      snapcat -f markdown --max-file-size 1048576 -o context.md

- Shallow tree (depth 2) ignoring all default ignore files:
      snapcat --max-depth 2 --ignore-files ""

- Verbose debug output while processing:
      snapcat -v


